The mesoporous WO3–TiO2 composite thin films coated on ITO substrate and annealed at 450, 500, and 600 °C were sensitized with a ruthenium based dye, and thereafter used as active electrodes in the construction of photochromic devices. Figure 3 shows the SEM cross-section image of the device constructed by using a WO3–TiO2 thin film coated on an ITO glass substrate and annealed at 450 °C. From bottom to top, Fig. 3 shows the glass substrate, the thin ITO layer (190 nm), the thick WO3–TiO2 composite layer (~800 nm) and the IC layer over the dye sensitized WO3–TiO2 composite layer. In this configuration, as the light (1 sun) is incident on the surface of the ICL, a dye molecule absorbs a photon. Then, an electron is rapidly injected from the excited state of the dye into the conduction band of the TiO2 present in the WO3–TiO2 layer, and diffuses to the WO3. Ionized dye molecules are reduced by I− in the ICL according to the reaction: 3I− → I3− + 2e−. Li ions intercalate into the WO3 such that the charges balance. Because of the injection of electrons, the WO3 is reduced and changes its color from transparent to blue according to the reaction:WO3+xLi++xe¯↔LixWO3transparentblue\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
